    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Better Judicial Elections</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>National Voting Rights Institute official John C Bonifaz letter on Oct 25 article calls for public financing of judicial elections in Florida and other states</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Florida Voters to Decide Judicial Selection'' (news article, Oct. 25):</p>
        <p>As the concern rises in many states about the problem of political contributors writing checks to judges, the debate over the solution must be broadened. Judicial elections do not need to be eliminated. They need to be publicly financed.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Florida Voters to Decide Judicial Selection'' (news article, Oct. 25):</p>
        <p>As the concern rises in many states about the problem of political contributors writing checks to judges, the debate over the solution must be broadened. Judicial elections do not need to be eliminated. They need to be publicly financed.</p>
        <p>Full public financing would do away with judicial candidates' raising large sums of money from lawyers and wealthy interests. It would also enable those seeking judgeships without support from the powerful to compete on a level playing field -- something that an appointive system rarely provides.</p>
        <p>JOHN C. BONIFAZ  Executive Director  National Voting Rights Institute  Boston, Oct. 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
